'''David Robert Ciardi''' (born 17 July 1969) is an [[United States|American]] [[astronomer]].  He received a bachelor's degree in physics and astronomy from [[Boston University]] in 1991, and a Ph.D. in physics from the [[University of Wyoming]] in 1997.

==Career==
Ciardi has published refereed journal articles across a wide range of topics, including exoplanets,<ref>{{cite journal  | authors = Ciardi, D. R., Fabrycky, D. C., Ford, E. B., Gautier, T. N., III, Howell, S. B., Lissauer, J. J., Ragozzine, D., & Rowe, J. F. | title = On the Relative Sizes of Planets within Kepler Multiple-candidate Systems | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2013   | volume = 763   | pages = 41   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/763/1/41   | bibcode = 2013ApJ...763...41C  |arxiv = 1212.1859 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal  |author1=van Eyken, J. C. |author2=Ciardi, D. R. | display-authors = etal | title = The PTF Orion Project: A Possible Planet Transiting a T-Tauri Star | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2012   | volume = 755   | pages = 42   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/755/1/42 | bibcode =   2012ApJ...755...42V|arxiv = 1206.1510 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Kane, S. R. |author2=Howell, S. B. |author3=Horch, E. P. |author4=Feng, Y. |author5=Hinkel, N. R. |author6=Ciardi, D. R. |author7=Everett, M. E. |author8=Howard, A. W. |author9=Wright, J. T. |last-author-amp=yes | title = Limits on Stellar Companions to Exoplanet Host Stars with Eccentric Planets | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2014   | volume = 785   | pages = 93   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/785/2/93   | bibcode = 2014ApJ...785...93K  |arxiv = 1401.1544 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal  | authors = Rowe, J. F., Bryson, S. T., Marcy, G. W., Lissauer, J. J., Jontof-Hutter, D., Mullally, F., Gilliland, R. L., Issacson, H., Ford, E., Howell, S. B., Borucki, W. J., Haas, M., Huber, D., Steffen, J. H., Thompson, S. E., Quintana, E., Barclay, T., Still, M., Fortney, J., Gautier, T. N., III, Hunter, R., Caldwell, D. A., Ciardi, D. R., Devore, E., Cochran, W., Jenkins, J., Agol, E., Carter, J. A., & Geary, J. | title = Validation of Kepler's Multiple Planet Candidates. III. Light Curve Analysis and Announcement of Hundreds of New Multi-planet Systems | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2014   | volume = 784   | pages = 45   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/784/1/45   | bibcode = 2014ApJ...784...45R  |arxiv = 1402.6534 }}</ref> star formation,<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Ciardi, D. R. |author2= Gómez Martín, C. |last-author-amp=yes | title = Star Formation in the Bok Globule CB54 | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2007   | volume = 664   | pages = 377   | doi = 10.1086/518651   | bibcode = 2007ApJ...664..377C  |arxiv = 0704.0428 }}</ref> interstellar dust,<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Ciardi, D. R. |author2=Wachter, S. |author3=Hoard, D. W. |author4=Howell, S. B. |author5=van Belle, G. T. |last-author-amp=yes | title = Spitzer Space Telescope Observations of Var Her 04: Possible Detection of Dust Formation in a Superoutbursting Tremendous Outburst Amplitude Dwarf Nova | journal = The Astronomical Journal | year = 2006   | volume = 132   | pages = 1989   | doi = 10.1086/508212   | bibcode = 2006AJ....132.1989C  |arxiv = astro-ph/0608083 }}</ref> molecular clouds,<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Ciardi, D. R. |author2=Woodward, C. E. |author3=Clemens, D. P. |author4=Harker, D. E. |author5=Rudy, R. J. |last-author-amp=yes| title = Morphology and Energetics of the Molecular Gas within a Core and a Diffuse Region in the Filamentary Dark Cloud GF 9 | journal = The Astronomical Journal | year = 2000   | volume = 120   | pages = 393   | doi = 10.1086/301436   | bibcode = 2000AJ....120..393C  }}</ref> and evolved stars.<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Ciardi, D. R. |author2=Howell, S. B. |author3=Hauschildt P. |author4=Allard, F. |last-author-amp=yes| title = The Relative Contributions to the Near-Infrared Emission in Short Period Cataclysmic Variables | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 1998   | volume = 504 | pages = 450   | doi = 10.1086/306081  | bibcode =   1998ApJ...504..450C}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal  |author1=van Belle, G. T. |author2=Paladini, C. |author3=Aringer, B. |author4=Hron, J. |author5=Ciardi, D. R. |last-author-amp=yes | title = The PTI Carbon Star Angular Size Survey: Effective Temperatures and Non-sphericity | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2013   | volume = 775   | pages = 45   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/775/1/45   | bibcode = 2013ApJ...775...45V  |arxiv = 1307.6585 }}</ref>  His observations of [[Vega]] using [[long-baseline interferometry]] with the [[Palomar Testbed Interferometer]] were the first to spatially resolve the debris disk around this star and to show that dust was present within 1 AU of the star - akin to the interplanetary dust in the [[Solar System]] that produces the [[zodiacal light]].<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Ciardi, D. R. |author2=van Belle, G. T. |author3=Akeson, R. L. |author4=Thompson, R. R. |author5=Lada, E. A. |author6= Howell, S. B. |last-author-amp=yes | title = On the Near-Infrared Size of Vega | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2001   | volume = 559   | pages = 1147   | doi = 10.1086/322345   | bibcode = 2001ApJ...559.1147C  |arxiv = astro-ph/0105561 }}</ref> This work led to the discovery of dust in the inner regions around other stars and leading to the discovery of a gap between the inner dust ring and the outer dust ring in many systems - the existence of which is still not understood.<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Akeson, R. L. |author2=Millan-Gabet, R. M. |author3=Ciardi, D. R. | display-authors = etal | title = Radial Structure in the TW Hya Circumstellar Disk | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2011   | volume = 728  | pages = 96   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/728/2/96 | bibcode = 2011ApJ...728...96A |citeseerx=10.1.1.659.9897}}</ref> Ciardi is a member of the Kepler Science Team and using data from the [[Kepler (spacecraft)|Kepler]] mission, Ciardi has published landmark works on the fundamental nature of stellar variability<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=Ciardi, D. R. |author2=von Braun, K. |author3=Bryden, G. |author4=van Eyken, J. |author5=Howell, S. B. |author6=Kane, S. R. |author7=Plavchan, P. |author8=Ramírez, S. V. |author9= Stauffer, J. R. |last-author-amp=yes | title = Characterizing the Variability of Stars with Early-release Kepler Data | journal = The Astronomical Journal | year = 2011   | volume = 141   | pages = 108   | doi = 10.1088/0004-6256/141/4/108   | bibcode = 2011AJ....141..108C  |arxiv = 1009.1840 }}</ref> and the relative sizes of planets in multi-planet systems<ref>{{cite journal  | authors = Ciardi, D. R., Fabrycky, D. C., Ford, E. B., Gautier, T. N., III, Howell, S. B., Lissauer, J. J., Ragozzine, D., & Rowe, J. F. | title = On the Relative Sizes of Planets within Kepler Multiple-candidate Systems | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2013   | volume = 763   | pages = 41   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/763/1/41   | bibcode = 2013ApJ...763...41C  |arxiv = 1212.1859 }}</ref> and has contributed to more than 100 exoplanet discovery papers, including many of the [[List of exoplanets discovered using the Kepler spacecraft|Kepler Mission discoveries]] and being the principal investigator of the [[Palomar Transient Factory|Palomar Transient Factory Orion Transit Survey]]<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=van Eyken, J. C. |author2=Ciardi, D. R. | display-authors = etal | title = The Palomar Transient Factory Orion Project: Eclipsing Binaries and Young Stellar Objects | journal = The Astronomical Journal | year = 2011   | volume = 142   | pages = 60  | doi = 10.1088/0004-6256/142/2/60 | bibcode = 2011AJ....142...60V |arxiv = 1106.3570 }}</ref> and co-discoverer of the first transiting planet around a newly formed [[T Tauri]] star in the 3-million-year-old star cluster surrounding [[25 Orionis]].<ref>{{cite journal  |author1=van Eyken, J. C. |author2=Ciardi, D. R. | display-authors = etal | title = The PTF Orion Project: A Possible Planet Transiting a T-Tauri Star | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | year = 2012   | volume = 755   | pages = 42   | doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/755/1/42 | bibcode =   2012ApJ...755...42V|arxiv = 1206.1510 }}</ref>

Ciardi completed his PhD at the University of Wyoming in 1997, and remained in Laramie for another year as a post-doctoral fellow.  He left Wyoming to become a post-doc at the University of Florida, ostensibly to work on the [[Wide Field Infrared Explorer]] (WIRE) mission.  The unfortunate failure of WIRE's main telescope immediately following launch sidetracked that research path; however, Ciardi remained at Florida and became a staff member with the infrared instrumentation group where he worked on an array of infrared instruments, including T-ReCS for the 8m telescope [[Gemini Observatory|Gemini South]] and [[Gran Telescopio Canarias#CanariCam|CanariCam]] for the 10m [[Gran Telescopio Canarias]].  In 2002, Ciardi took a staff astronomer position at the [[NExScI|NASA Exoplanet Science Institute]]; he is currently the NExScI Chief Scientist, and is a Member of the Professional Staff at [[Caltech]].

== Awards and honors ==
In 2016, Ciardi was awarded the [[NASA Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal]] for his work on Kepler and his contributions to the confirmation of Kepler's exoplanets which have led to the characterization of planets ranging in size from Jupiters to Earths.  The [[NASA Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal]] is awarded to individuals for unusually significant scientific contributions toward achievement of aeronautical or space exploration goals. Asteroid [[26312 Ciardi]] was named in his honor.<ref name="MPC-object" /> The official {{MoMP|26312|naming citation}} was published by the [[Minor Planet Center]] on 18 May 2019 ({{small|[[Minor Planet Circulars|M.P.C.]] 114954}}).<ref name="MPC-Circulars-Archive" />

